AROUND 16:00 HOURS ON OCTOBER 25, 1989, A CONTRACT CARRIER VAN LOADED WITH DRUMS OF CHEMICALS OWNED BY THE WESTERN COMPANY OF NORTH AMERICA, WAS TRAVELING WEST ON ONTERSTATE HIGHWAY 70, APPROACHING THE EISENHOWER TUNNEL, DESTINED FOR VERNAL, UTAH.  ONE OF THE STEEL CHEMICAL DRUMS HAD A HOLE IN IT ON THE SIDE OF THE DRUM CLOSE TO THE TOP.  THIS HOLE WAS PROBABLY CAUSED BY A FORK LIFT DURING LOADING.  THE LEAKING DRUM CONTINED WESTERN CLAY MASTER-4 (A WESTERN PRODCUT-LIQUID MIXTURE CONTAINING APPROXIMATELY 10 % METHANOL).  THE DRUM HAD LEAKED AROUND 7 GALLONS (60 POUNDS) OF PRODUCT ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER (THIS FACT WAS DETERMINED BECAUSE 48 GALLONS OF LIQUID WAS RECOVERED FROM THE DRUM WHEN WESTERN PERSONNEL REMOVED THE BAD DRUM FROM THE TRUCK. WHEN THE TRUCK STARTED UP THE 6% GRADE TO THE EISENHOWER TUNNEL, THE SPILLED LIQUID BEGAN TO LEAK OUT THE BACK OF THE TRAILER.  THIS WAS DETECTED ON THE OBSERVATON SYSTEM OF THE TUNNEL AUTHORITY AND THE AUTHORITY STOPPED THE TRUCK AS IT EXITED THE TUNNEL. THE WESTERN COMPANY IN FORT WORTH WAS NOTIFIED WHO THEN NOTIFIED THE WESTERN COMPANY IN BRIGHTON.  PERSONNEL FROM BRIGHTON WENT TO THE TRUCK LOCATION AND REMOVED THE BAD DRUM AND REMAINING PRODUCT.  ALL EVENTS TOOK PLACE BETWEEN 3 AND 5 HOURS TO COMPLETE AFTER THE INCIDENT WAS DISCOVERED. I UNDERSTAND THAT TWO PEOPLE (TRUCK DRIVER AND A TUNNEL AUTHORITY PERSON) WENT TO THE HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION AND WERE LATER RELEASED.  I ALSO UNDERSTAND THAT A LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE GRUOP WAS CALLED AND RESPONDED TO THE LOCATION.

A TOW TRUCK WAS CALLED, THE TRAILER WAS REMOVED FROM THE DITCH AFTER EMPTYING, HOOKED BACK UP TO OUR TRUCK AND PULLED TO OUR TERMINAL IN PORTLAND, OREGON.

column168: AT APPROX. 8:25 PM, ON OCT. 8, 1989, A VEHICLE DRIVEN BY MR JIM RICHARDSON, DELIVERING PACKAGES FOR DEL-MED, INC., COLLIDED WITH A VEHICLE 12 MILES WE ST OF WESTON, WV, ON US RTE 33. AT APPROX. 8:45PM, EMERGENCY PERSONNEL (FIR E DEPT., STATE POLICE, SHERIFF'S DEPT.) BEGAN ARRIVING AT THE ACCIDENT SITE . A PERIMETER OF 150 FT WAS ESTABLISHED AROUND THE VEHICLE. THE FIRE DEPT A PPROACHED THE VEHICLE FROM THIS DISTANCE USING A CDV-700 GM SURVEY METER.NO UNUSUAL RADIATION LEVELS WERE OBSERVED. THE FIRE DEPT, WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF MR. RICHARDSON OPENED THE REAR DOOR TO THE VEHICLE. THEY OBSERVED THAT ALL PACKAGES WERE INTACT AND IN THE BLOCK AND BRACED POSITION. SURVEYS OF T HE VEHICLE AND SURROUNDING AREAS INDICATED NO RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL WAS RELE ASED. AS NO PACKAGES WERE OBSERVED DAMAGED OR LEAKING, THE EMERGENCY PERSON NEL CONTINUED THEIR ASSISTANCE TO THE PEOPLE IN THE PASSENGER VEHICLE AND M R. RICHARDSON. HIGHWAY CONDITIONS WERE FOG AND A WET ROAD SURFACE. A MEMBER OF THE FIRE DEPT., RUSSELL PARKS, REPORTED TO BE A RADIOLOGIST AT THE VA HOSPITAL IN CLARKSON, WV, WAS PRESENT AT THE ACCIDENT SITE. IT WAS T HE OPINION OF DR. PARKS THAT NO PACKAGES WERE DAMAGED IN THE ACCIDENT, REIT IERATING THE OBSERVATION OF OTHER EMERGENCY PERSONNEL. INJURED DURING THE ACCIDENT WERE MR. JIM RICHARDSON AND THE DRIVER OF THE P ASSENGER VEHICLE AND THE FOUR PASSENGERS IN HIS VEHICLE.ALL INJURED PEOPLE WERE INITIALLY TAKEN TO STONEWALL JACKSON MEMORIAL HOSPITAL AND TREATED AND RELEASED, OR HELD FOR OBSERVATION. ONE PERSON IN HE PASSENGER VEHICLE REPO RTED TO BE AN ELDERLY FEMALE, WAS TAKEN TO A NEIGHBORING HOSPITAL FOR FURTH ER OBSERVATIONS. THERE WERE NO DEATHS RELATED TO THIS ACCIDENT. THE EXACT S EVERITY OF ALL INJURIES HAVE NOT BEEN REPORTED TO ME BY LOCAL AUTHORITIES. A FLATBED TOWING SERVICE WAS UTILIZED TO TAKE THE VAN CONTAINING THE RADIOA CTIVE MATERIAL TO STONEWALL JACKSON MEMORIAL HOSPITAL. THE PACKAGES WERE UN LOADED FROM THE VAN AND PLACED IN A SECURE AREA OF THE HOSPITAL OF THE HOSP ITAL BY DR. PARKS. THE VAN WAS THEN REMOVED TO A SECURE LOADING AREA. A SUR VEY OF THE VEHICLE REQUESTED BY ME ON THE FOLLOWING DAY INDICATED NO CONTAM INATION TO BE PRESENT. I REQUESTED THIS SURVEY, AS SURVEY RESULTS AT THE TI ME THE VEHICLE CONTENTS WERE REMOVED WERE NOT AVAILABLE TO ME. ON BOARD THE VAN WERE 7 MO-99/TC-99M GENERATORS TOTALLING APPROX. 9.2 CI, 4 XE-133 COMPRESSED GAS AMPULES TOTALLING APPROX.0.5 CI AND 3 T1-201 TOTALLI NG APPROX. 0.015 CI. THESE PACKAGES WERE PICKED UP AT STONEWALL JACKSOM MEM ORIAL HOSPITAL BY MR. MARK SHADDOCK FOR DEL-MED, INC. MR SHADDOCK COMPLETED THE DELIVERY OF THE PACKAGES.

column168: WHILE LOADING TRAILER TRUCK WITH SKID OF STEEL DRUMS CONTAINING SODIUM CYAN IDE, SKID FELL INSIDE TRAILER DAMAGING ONE OF THE DRUMS. THE DRUM CONTAINED 220 POUNDS OF SODIUM CYANIDE BRICK FORM. A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE BRICKS WERE RELEASED INSIDE THE TRUCK. KEVIN CRITCHLEY OF GUMM CHEMICAL, AND TRUCK DDRIVER JOHN MATUS, WERE APPARE NTLY IN THE TRAILER ATTEMPTING TO MOVE REMAINING DRUMS WHEN KEVIN BEGAN TO FEEL A "SCRATCHING" IN HIS THROAT. BOTH MEN LEFT THE TRUCK AND CALLED LEROY STAGG AT OUR MAIN OFFICE IN KEARNEY, AT APPROXIMATELY 3:15PM. STAGG AND I ARRIVED AT THE WAREHOUSE AT ABOUT 3;30. KEVIN CRITICHLEY WAS ST ILL COMPLAINING OF A SCRATCHED THROAT AND WAS SENT TO THE HOSPITAL. THE DRI VER WAS ALSO SENT TO THE CLARA MAAS HOSPITAL IN BELLEVILLE. THE SPILL CYNOBRICKS WERE RECOVERED AND WEIGHED AND TOTAL WEIGHT OF RELEASE D MATERIAL WAS DETERMINED TO BE 8.5 LLBS. THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF SODIUM CY ANIDE TO THE ENVIRONMENT OR TO ANYWATERWAY OR STORM SEWERS. THE MINOR RELEA SE WAS CONTAINED ENTIRELY WITHIN THE TRAILER, AND 100% OF THE MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED. THE NJ DEP WAS NOTIFIED THRU MR. WALTER JENICEK AT THE WEST ORANGE LOCATION AT 3:40 PM. THE E-MAC TRUCKING COMPANY WAS ALSO NOTIFIED. THE NRC CASE NUM BER IS 176-21. BOTHE KEVIN CRITCHLEY AND MR. MATUS WERE EXAMINED AT THE CLARA MAAS HOSPITA L EMERGENCY ROOM, DETERMINED TO BE IN GOOD HEALTH AND RELEASED. BOTH MEN RE TURNED TO WORK ON 09/06/89.
